---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Navbar from '../../components/Navbar.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Upscaler Studio — EDITH Dev Studio"
  description="Upscaler Studio is a local-first Windows desktop AI upscaling product direction from EDITH Dev Studio, designed around image and video workflows."
>
  <div class="site-shell">
    <Navbar />

    <main>
      <section class="hero">
        <div class="orb one"></div>
        <div class="orb two"></div>

        <div class="container hero-grid">
          <div>
            <p class="eyebrow">Upscaler Studio · by EDITH Dev Studio</p>
            <h1>Local AI upscaling with a product-grade desktop direction.</h1>
            <p class="hero-copy">
              Upscaler Studio is being positioned as a premium Windows-first tool for image and video upscaling, built around local processing, batch workflows, review, and cleaner control.
            </p>

            <div class="cta-row">
              <a href="/pricing" class="btn btn-primary">View launch model</a>
              <a href="/support" class="btn btn-secondary">Contact support</a>
            </div>

            <div class="metrics">
              <div class="metric">
                <h3>Local-first</h3>
                <p class="muted">Desktop processing direction</p>
              </div>
              <div class="metric">
                <h3>Image + Video</h3>
                <p class="muted">One product identity</p>
              </div>
              <div class="metric">
                <h3>Batch-ready</h3>
                <p class="muted">Workflow-oriented surface</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="hero-card float-panel">
            <div class="window-dots">
              <span></span><span></span><span></span>
            </div>

            <div class="preview-grid">
              <div class="preview-box input">Input preview</div>

              <div class="process-card">
                <strong>Product direction</strong>
                <p class="muted" style="margin-top: .35rem;">
                  Model choice, queueing, review, and export flow presented as one coherent desktop experience.
                </p>
                <div class="progress"><i></i></div>
              </div>

              <div class="preview-box output">Enhanced output</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <div class="container">
          <div class="section-head">
            <p class="eyebrow">Who it is for</p>
            <h2>Built for people who care about output and control.</h2>
            <p class="lead">
              The strongest product positioning is not “AI for everyone”, but a more serious tool direction for users who value workflow clarity, local ownership, and better packaging.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="grid-3">
            <article class="card">
              <h3>Creators</h3>
              <p style="margin-top: .7rem;">Useful for users who want higher-quality image or video output without depending entirely on browser-based tools.</p>
            </article>

            <article class="card">
              <h3>Power users</h3>
              <p style="margin-top: .7rem;">Better suited to people who care about presets, batch operations, visible process flow, and desktop control.</p>
            </article>

            <article class="card">
              <h3>Future customers</h3>
              <p style="margin-top: .7rem;">The product page should already feel commercial-grade, even before final screenshots, legal text, and checkout go live.</p>
            </article>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section alt">
        <div class="container">
          <div class="section-head">
            <p class="eyebrow">Why local-first matters</p>
            <h2>A stronger value proposition than “just another AI tool”.</h2>
            <p class="lead">
              The differentiator is not only upscale capability. It is the combination of local control, desktop seriousness, and a workflow that feels intentional.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="grid-3">
            <article class="card">
              <h3>More control</h3>
              <p style="margin-top: .7rem;">A local-first product direction gives users a clearer sense of ownership over files, workflow, and machine-level execution.</p>
            </article>

            <article class="card">
              <h3>Better privacy posture</h3>
              <p style="margin-top: .7rem;">Not every user wants a cloud-native path for media processing. That tension can become part of the product’s identity.</p>
            </article>

            <article class="card">
              <h3>Desktop credibility</h3>
              <p style="margin-top: .7rem;">A polished Windows-first presentation helps the product feel distinct from a simple wrapper around command-line tooling.</p>
            </article>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <div class="container">
          <div class="section-head">
            <p class="eyebrow">Workflow highlights</p>
            <h2>What the product page should communicate clearly.</h2>
          </div>

          <div class="grid-2">
            <article class="card">
              <h3>Image and video scope</h3>
              <p style="margin-top: .7rem;">One product identity built around both still-image enhancement and video-oriented processing direction.</p>
            </article>

            <article class="card">
              <h3>Queue and review</h3>
              <p style="margin-top: .7rem;">Batch-ready flow, result comparison, and history visibility matter more than a single “upscale now” button.</p>
            </article>

            <article class="card">
              <h3>Cleaner product surface</h3>
              <p style="margin-top: .7rem;">A premium site should suggest stronger packaging, better UX, and clearer product logic from the first screen.</p>
            </article>

            <article class="card">
              <h3>Release-aware presentation</h3>
              <p style="margin-top: .7rem;">The page can feel serious without claiming that download, legal, packaging, and commercial readiness are already final.</p>
            </article>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section alt">
        <div class="container">
          <div class="section-head">
            <p class="eyebrow">Launch model</p>
            <h2>Simple first. Expand later.</h2>
            <p class="lead">
              The current recommended go-to-market structure is a free trial plus a single Studio License, presented as the likely launch model rather than as fully live checkout.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="pricing-grid">
            <article class="price-card">
              <span class="badge">Planned entry point</span>
              <h3 style="margin-top: 1rem;">Trial</h3>
              <div class="price">Free</div>
              <ul class="price-list">
                <li>Evaluation-first path</li>
                <li>Lower-friction adoption</li>
                <li>Stronger trust at first touch</li>
              </ul>
            </article>

            <article class="price-card featured">
              <span class="badge">Planned launch option</span>
              <h3 style="margin-top: 1rem;">Studio License</h3>
              <div class="price">€49</div>
              <ul class="price-list">
                <li>Simple premium structure</li>
                <li>Cleaner product messaging</li>
                <li>Good first public pricing test</li>
              </ul>
            </article>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <div class="container">
          <div class="section-head">
            <p class="eyebrow">FAQ direction</p>
            <h2>Answer the questions a serious visitor will already have.</h2>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-grid grid-3">
            <article class="faq-item">
              <h3>Is Upscaler Studio already fully released?</h3>
              <p class="muted" style="margin-top: .6rem;">The website can present the intended product direction now, while final release depends on packaging, quality, and compliance gates.</p>
            </article>

            <article class="faq-item">
              <h3>Why emphasize local-first?</h3>
              <p class="muted" style="margin-top: .6rem;">Because local control, privacy posture, and desktop ownership are part of the product’s differentiation strategy.</p>
            </article>

            <article class="faq-item">
              <h3>Why keep EDITH separate from the product name?</h3>
              <p class="muted" style="margin-top: .6rem;">Because EDITH Dev Studio should remain the umbrella publisher brand for future products beyond Upscaler Studio.</p>
            </article>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
    </main>

    <Footer />
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
